default3.9.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThere are potential 
defaultrisks
default associated with the promotion of fuels like biomass as these may reduce carbon dioxide emissions while contributing to the problem of climate change through their high black carbon
default emissions.  The United Nations Economic Commission for Europe (UNECE) noted the risk of biomass resulting in an increase in black carbon emissions in a 2010 report [AEGPL].
default&#xa0;
default3.10.
default 
defaultLP
default 
defaultG
defaultas
default produces low levels of particle and NOx emissions, meaning that it does no
defaultt pollute the air as much as many other energy sources.  For three priority pollutants; hydrocarbons,  nitrous oxides  and particle matter, as well as on carbon monoxide, toxics and heavy metals, gaseous fuels’ air pollution footprints are lower than those
default of liquid fuels (heating oil and residual oil) and dramatically lower than those of solid fuels (coal and wood). [LPG and Air Quality: A Scientific Review, Atlantic consulting].
